definitions.example: ribald Chaucerian pilgrimages

definitions.definition: an admirer, imitator, or student of the works of the English writer Geoffrey Chaucer.
definitions.example: every English department wants a Chaucerian

definitions.definition: a woman's loose gown of a kind fashionable during the 17th and 18th centuries.

dictionaryEntry.origin: alteration of French manteau, influenced by Mantua.

definitions.definition: an adherent of Jainism.

dictionaryEntry.origin: via Hindi from Sanskrit jaina ‘of or concerning a Jina’ (a great Jain teacher or holy man, literally ‘victor’), from ji- ‘conquer’ or jyā- ‘overcome’.

definitions.definition: (in ancient Mesopotamia) a rectangular stepped tower, sometimes surmounted by a temple. Ziggurats are first attested in the late 3rd millennium BC and probably inspired the biblical story of the Tower of Babel (Gen. 11:1–9).

dictionaryEntry.origin: from Akkadian ziqqurratu .

definitions.definition: a member of a North American people living chiefly on the Great Plains, especially in Wyoming.
the Algonquian language of the Arapaho, now almost extinct.
relating to the Arapaho or their language.

dictionaryEntry.origin: from Crow alappahó, literally ‘many tattoo marks’.

definitions.definition: a kind of crane with a movable pivoted arm for moving heavy weights, especially on a ship.
the framework over an oil well or similar boring, holding the drilling machinery.

dictionaryEntry.origin: early 17th century (denoting a hangman, also the gallows): from Derrick, the surname of a London hangman.

definitions.definition: the shop or business of a chandler.
a movable frame on which a coffin or a corpse is placed before burial or cremation or on which they are carried to the grave.

dictionaryEntry.origin: Old English bēr, of Germanic origin; related to German Bahre, also to bear1.

definitions.definition: an extended urban area, typically consisting of several towns merging with the suburbs of a central city.
definitions.example: the major conurbations of London and Birmingham

dictionaryEntry.origin: early 20th century: from con- ‘together’ + Latin urbs, urb- ‘city’ + -ation.

definitions.definition: another term for the Dakota people of North America or their language. See Dakota2.
relating to the Sioux or their language.

dictionaryEntry.origin: North American French, from Nadouessioux from Ojibwa (Ottawa dialect) nātowēssiwak, by substitution of the French plural ending -x for the Ojibwa plural -ak .

definitions.definition: a room used for communal meals in an educational or religious institution.

dictionaryEntry.origin: late Middle English: from late Latin refectorium, from Latin reficere ‘refresh, renew’, from re- ‘back’ + facere ‘make’.

definitions.definition: (in Spain and Spanish America) a fortified military settlement.

dictionaryEntry.origin: Spanish, from Latin praesidium ‘garrison’.
